data.content:
## What breaks in .NET 11

The Cosmos DB provider **never had native sync support** — it internally wrapped async calls (sync-over-async). EF Core 9 started throwing `InvalidOperationException` for sync operations by default, offering a temporary opt-in escape hatch. **In .NET 11, that opt-in is removed entirely.**

Every synchronous LINQ operator and `SaveChanges()` call against the Cosmos provider will throw `InvalidOperationException` — no configuration can re-enable it.

## The fix — convert to async

```csharp
public class ProductRepository
{
    private readonly CosmosDbContext _context;

    public async Task<List<Product>> GetAllAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.ToListAsync();
    }

    public async Task<Product> GetByIdAsync(int id)
    {
        return await _context.Products.FirstAsync(p => p.Id == id);
    }

    public async Task<int> GetCountAsync()
    {
        return await _context.Products.CountAsync();
    }

    public async Task SaveAsync(Product product)
    {
        _context.Products.Add(product);
        await _context.SaveChangesAsync();
    }
}
```

**Key changes:**
| Sync (broken) | Async replacement |
|---|---|
| `ToList()` | `await ToListAsync()` |
| `First()` | `await FirstAsync()` |
| `Count()` | `await CountAsync()` |
| `SaveChanges()` | `await SaveChangesAsync()` |

You'll also need to propagate `async`/`await` up through your call chain (controllers, services, etc.). The `Add()` call remains synchronous — it only tracks the entity in memory and doesn't hit Cosmos.
